FORCED_TERMINATION

public static final java.lang.String FORCED_TERMINATION
The message of a forced shutdown. This is important, as we look for it when the component is terminated, and can use its presence to infer that the helper thread did the work.

sfPingChildren

protected void sfPingChildren()
Called by CompoundImpl.sfPing(Object) to run through the list of children and ping each in turn. If any child fails, PrimImpl.sfLivenessFailure(Object,Object,Throwable) is called and the iteration continues.

Override this method to implement different child ping behaviour.

Overrides:
sfPingChildren in class CompoundImpl

sfPingActionAndHandleFailure

protected void sfPingActionAndHandleFailure()
Ping the action. If we get a liveness failure (i.e. the child has terminated, we check to see if it was actually expected, in which case this is not a problem. We note and ignore it. The reason for this special handling is related to race conditions in termination...a ping could be received and processed while we are getting ready to deal with terminated children. This handler ignores such situations

onChildTerminated

protected boolean onChildTerminated(TerminationRecord childStatus,
                                    Prim child)
This is an override point; it is where subclasses get to change their workflow depending on what happens underneath. It is only called outside of component termination, i.e. when EventCompoundImpl.isWorkflowTerminating() is false, and when the comp parameter is a child, that is sfContainsChild(comp) holds. If the the method returns true, the event is forwarded up the object hierarchy, which will eventually trigger a component termination.

Always return false if you start new components from this method!

Overrides:
onChildTerminated in class EventCompoundImpl
Parameters:
childStatus - exit record of the component
child - child component that is terminating
Returns:
true if the termination event is to be forwarded up the chain.
